3:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["How Funding Works on ","Bluefin"]}]
4:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bluefin calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium/discount between perpetual and mark prices, with payments exchanged between long and short positions. The platform's Sui-based architecture enables near-instant settlement with minimal gas costs, making frequent arbitrage strategies more profitable. Funding rates are capped at ±0.75% per hour to prevent extreme situations, while the order book model ensures transparent price discovery. Unlike AMM-based DEXs, Bluefin's matching engine provides consistent execution quality even during high volatility periods."}]
5:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ENA","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA exhibits elevated funding rate volatility due to its connection to Ethena's USDe stablecoin protocol and sUSDe staking rewards. The token's DeFi utility drives periods of high demand coinciding with Ethena protocol growth phases, creating predictable funding rate patterns. ENA's mid-tier volume on Bluefin provides adequate liquidity for arbitrage while maintaining higher rate spreads than major pairs."}]]}]
6:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA funding rates on Bluefin typically range from -0.01% to +0.15% hourly, with significant spikes during Ethena protocol announcements and USDe adoption milestones. The token shows strong positive correlation with broader DeFi rallies, often maintaining elevated positive rates for 24-48 hour periods. Rate volatility increases substantially around quarterly Ethena governance proposals and sUSDe yield adjustments. Weekend periods generally see compressed rates due to reduced institutional activity, creating mean reversion opportunities."}]]}]
7:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between Bluefin and centralized exchanges like Binance or OKX frequently yields 0.02-0.08% hourly when ENA funding diverges. Bluefin's lower trading volume can create temporary rate dislocations, especially during high-impact Ethena news events. The platform's 0.02% maker rebate partially offsets funding costs when maintaining neutral positions across multiple venues. Sui ecosystem growth phases often drive sustained positive funding on Bluefin while CEX rates remain neutral."}]]}]
8:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA's sensitivity to regulatory news affecting stablecoins can trigger rapid funding rate reversals and increase mark-to-market risk. Bluefin's relatively low liquidity compared to major DEXs may result in wider spreads during volatile periods, impacting arbitrage profitability. Sui network congestion during high-activity periods could delay funding settlements, creating temporary exposure gaps. The platform's early-stage status in the Sui ecosystem introduces smart contract risks and potential liquidity crunches during market stress."}]]}]
9:["$","$Le",null,{"items":[{"question":"What makes ENA funding rates unique on Bluefin compared to CEXs?","answer":"Bluefin's Sui-based infrastructure and lower institutional presence create more pronounced rate movements during DeFi-specific events. The hourly settlement frequency combined with the platform's order book model often results in less efficient arbitrage, maintaining rate spreads longer than on major centralized exchanges."},{"question":"How does Bluefin's maker rebate affect ENA funding arbitrage profitability?","answer":"The 0.02% maker rebate can offset negative funding payments when providing liquidity on the beneficial side of rate differentials. This rebate structure makes Bluefin particularly attractive for delta-neutral strategies during periods of sustained funding rate trends."},{"question":"What are the optimal position sizes for ENA funding arbitrage on Bluefin?","answer":"Given ENA's mid-tier volume, positions should generally stay under $50,000 to avoid significant market impact. Larger positions risk moving the funding rate against your position and may experience difficulty with timely exits during volatile periods."},{"question":"How do Sui network dynamics affect ENA perpetual trading on Bluefin?","answer":"Sui's fast finality benefits frequent rebalancing strategies, but network adoption phases can create temporary congestion. ENA's connection to multi-chain DeFi protocols means cross-chain arbitrage opportunities may arise when Sui performance diverges from Ethereum mainnet activity."}]}]
